You have 16 HCP and a balanced hand with stoppers in every suit. What do you open?
[BID 1N] With a balanced hand in the 15 to 17 range, one notrump describes your strength and shape in a single bid. Open one notrump.
[POST-AUCTION]
Partner raised your one notrump straight to three notrump, so your side has 28 combined HCP and you declare. East sits with a long heart suit headed by the \H KQ, and your \H A is the only thing holding it back. That makes East the danger hand: if East ever gets on lead, those hearts cash and beat you. West is harmless — short in hearts, with no way to reach partner.
[show NS]
Between the two hands you have stoppers and the makings of a ninth trick, but only one heart stopper — your \H A — so the whole deal turns on which finesse you choose. Your two finesses sit in spades and clubs. Here it's the club finesse — leading toward dummy's \C KJ — that loses only to West if it fails, the safe hand. The spade finesse — leading toward your \S KJ — would lose to East, the danger hand. So take the club finesse and avoid the spade play; the club finesse keeps East off lead even when it loses.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You declare three notrump. East has length in hearts and your \H A is the lone stopper, so plan to keep East off lead while you develop a ninth trick.
[ROLE leader][STAGE auction-end]
Partner raised one notrump to three notrump, so declarer has the balanced strength. Look at your own long suit and decide whether to attack or sit back.
[ROLE defender][STAGE auction-end]
Declarer is in three notrump. You hold a long heart suit headed by the \H KQ — if you can get on lead, those hearts are the setting tricks.
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \S3. Attack your longest suit against notrump — fourth-best from your spade nine-eight-five-three-two works to set up tricks before declarer gets organised.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West leads the \S3, which looks like a fourth-best — if so, by the rule of eleven only four higher cards lie outside the West hand, and you and dummy hold all of them, so nothing's free for the defense. Win in hand and count your tricks; the spade lead doesn't touch your lone heart stopper, so keep the \H A for the hearts. The ninth trick is a finesse — take the club finesse, which loses only to safe West, and steer clear of the spade finesse that would let dangerous East in.
[ROLE defender][STAGE post-lead]
Your hearts are the setting tricks, but only if you can reach them. Watch which suit declarer attacks and grab the lead the moment a finesse runs to your side, then cash your hearts.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Choosing the club finesse over the spade finesse was the whole deal — it could only lose to safe West, never to dangerous East. Nicely judged, and well played.
[ROLE leader][STAGE post-play]
Leading your long suit was the right idea. Have a look at whether your defense ever got partner on lead to cash those hearts.
[ROLE defender][STAGE post-play]
Your hearts were the setting tricks all along. The key was getting on lead in time — see whether declarer's safe finesse kept you out.
}
