You have 16 HCP and a balanced hand with three aces and stoppers in every suit. What do you open?
[BID 1N] With a balanced hand in the 15 to 17 range, one notrump describes your strength and shape in a single bid. Open one notrump.
[POST-AUCTION]
Partner raised your one notrump straight to three notrump, so your side has 26 combined HCP and you declare. East sits with a long heart suit headed by the \H KQ, and your \H A is the only thing holding it back. That makes East the danger hand: if East ever gets on lead, those hearts cash and beat you. West is harmless — short in hearts, with no way to reach partner.
[show NS]
Between the two hands you have stoppers and the makings of a ninth trick, but only one heart stopper — your \H A — so the whole deal turns on which finesse you choose. You'd normally have to pick a finesse here, but on this layout both queens — the \S Q and the \C Q — sit with West, the safe hand. Either finesse loses only to West if it fails, so neither one can let the danger hand in. Take whichever you need; you're never at risk of East gaining the lead.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You declare three notrump. East has length in hearts and your \H A is the lone stopper, so plan to keep East off lead while you develop a ninth trick.
[ROLE leader][STAGE auction-end]
Partner raised one notrump to three notrump, so declarer has the balanced strength. Look at your own long suit and decide whether to attack or sit back.
[ROLE defender][STAGE auction-end]
Declarer is in three notrump. You hold a long heart suit headed by the \H KQ — if you can get on lead, those hearts are the setting tricks.
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \S3, fourth-best from your longest suit, spades \SQT932. Against notrump you attack your own length to build tricks — don't lead the singleton heart, which would only help declarer in the danger hand's long suit.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West leads the \S3, which looks like a fourth-best, suggesting about five spades — handily a suit you're glad to see, since East is the danger hand with the long hearts. Win the spade and go after your ninth trick knowing both missing queens sit with safe West: either the spade or the club finesse is safe here, because even if it loses it loses to West, never letting dangerous East in to cash hearts. Take whichever you need and bring it home.
[ROLE defender][STAGE post-lead]
Your hearts are the setting tricks, but only if you can reach them. Watch which suit declarer attacks and grab the lead the moment a finesse runs to your side, then cash your hearts.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
With both queens offside-but-safe in the West hand, you were free to take your finesse without fear — nothing could put East in. Cleanly played.
[ROLE leader][STAGE post-play]
Leading your long suit was the right idea. Have a look at whether your defense ever got partner on lead to cash those hearts.
[ROLE defender][STAGE post-play]
Your hearts were the setting tricks all along. The key was getting on lead in time — see whether declarer's safe finesse kept you out.
